This usually costs $60.00-$100.00. They either can't, or won't, fix anything properly, & they do not stand behind their work. They are very expensive; also. We would not recommend you send a toy scope, or a Tasco (same thing actually), to ABO; much less a prized Redfield, such as an Illuminator, Golden 5 Star, or a Low Pro.That said; there are several other scope repair companies; there has to be a couple of them that are reputable; who will disassemble, & clean a Redfield.The range finder in these scopes, will work in low light, cold, wet, rainy, & snowy conditions. Every place a laser range finder, won't work. Same goes for the bullet drop compensator. They are hands down, the best hunting scope ever produced. Why Leupold doesn't put them back into production, is beyond me.One last thing. If you hunt in cold, wet conditions, you should always drop a heat pad over your scope, a couple days before the hunt. title: For Sale:  Gwinn Firearms Bushmaster  Pistol the one that started it all for Bushmaster
postcontent: I have for you a very rare Gwinn Firearms Bushmaster Pistol.  This is the bullpup pistol that Mack Gwinn began making in the early 1970's in Bangor Maine that led to the company becoming Bushmaster.  There is only one other like it for sale in the US and probably the world and this is a far nicer example as it appears nearly unfired and aside from a few nicks on the receiver that can be easily touched up, in near mint condition.  The Bushmaster Pistol is not an AR, although it shares a few of the ARs fire control system and it uses the standard AR magazine and it was the first AR style weapon to use a gas piston and rod rather than a gas tube.  Yeah, 50 years ago... It is unique for many other reasons but something it does is really special, the weapon cants on its axis 38 degrees one way or the other depending on your circumstances or hand you are firing with, otherwise it ejects from the top.  I could go on but go read about the little bullpup and shoot me an email if you are interested in this rare and very special piece. This is number 0018xx of about 3400 and that puts its production date at about 1974.  $1800 or trade for a 16 or 18 inch Springfield SOCOM or Squad Rifle.
